[{"location":"reference/","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"reference/","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"Modules = [StrongFieldApproximation]","category":"page"},{"location":"reference/#StrongFieldApproximation.Diagram","page":"Reference","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.Diagram","text":"Diagram(path, couplings)\n\nGoldstone diagram describing a strong-field process, i.e. after an initial photoionization event, the ion and photoelectron are propagated separately (at the chosen level of approximation, typically Volkov waves are used for the photoelectrons). By interacting with the external field, the ion state may change, and through electron (re)scattering, both photoelectron and ion state may change.\n\nThe diagram is specified using a path of pairs (in antichronological order), where each pair designates (resultant ion channel, interaction), where interaction is an index to one of the couplings. The special value interaction == 0 corresponds to the initial ionization event, and should appear once and only once, at the end of path (i.e. the first event).\n\nExamples\n\njulia> couplings = (StrongFieldApproximation.DipoleCoupling,\n                    StrongFieldApproximation.CoulombCoupling)\n(StrongFieldApproximation.DipoleCoupling, StrongFieldApproximation.CoulombCoupling)\n\njulia> Diagram([(1,0)], couplings)\nGoldstone Diagram:\n   |0‚ü©\n  ‚ï±   ‚ï≤‚áú\n 1‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê§\n\n\njulia> Diagram([(2,1),(1,0)], couplings)\nGoldstone Diagram:\n   |0‚ü©\n  ‚ï±   ‚ï≤‚áú\n 1‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê©\n ‚áù‚îÉ   ‚îÇ\n 2‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê§\n\n\njulia> Diagram([(2,2),(1,0)], couplings)\nGoldstone Diagram:\n   |0‚ü©\n  ‚ï±   ‚ï≤‚áú\n 1‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê©\n  ‚î†‚îà‚îà‚îà‚î§\n 2‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê§\n\n\njulia> Diagram([(1,2),(2,2),(1,0)], couplings)\nGoldstone Diagram:\n   |0‚ü©\n  ‚ï±   ‚ï≤‚áú\n 1‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê©\n  ‚î†‚îà‚îà‚îà‚î§\n 2‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê™\n  ‚î†‚îà‚îà‚îà‚î§\n 1‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê§\n\n\njulia> Diagram([(3,1),(1,1),(2,2),(1,0)], couplings)\nGoldstone Diagram:\n   |0‚ü©\n  ‚ï±   ‚ï≤‚áú\n 1‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê©\n  ‚î†‚îà‚îà‚îà‚î§\n 2‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê™\n ‚áù‚îÉ   ‚îÇ\n 1‚îÉ   ‚îÇ\n ‚áù‚îÉ   ‚îÇ\n 3‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê§\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"reference/#StrongFieldApproximation.Diagram-Tuple{AbstractVector{T} where T, StrongFieldApproximation.System}","page":"Reference","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.Diagram","text":"Diagram(path::AbstractVector{Tuple{Int,Int}}, system)\n\nConvenience constructor that sets up the Diagram given a path and the couplings present in system. If path is empty, the diagram corresponding to photoionization into the first ionization of channel of system will automatically be generated.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationChannel","page":"Reference","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationChannel","text":"IonizationChannel(E, st)\n\nRepresents an ionization channel with energy E above the neutral (which is taken to have energy 0 Ha).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"reference/#StrongFieldApproximation.RangeIterator-Tuple{Int64, Int64}","page":"Reference","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.RangeIterator","text":"RangeIterator(n::Int,k::Int)\n\nReturns an iterator splitting the range 1:n into min(k,n) parts of (almost) equal size.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#StrongFieldApproximation.System","page":"Reference","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.System","text":"System\n\nDescribes the combined system of atom/molecule (in terms of ionization channels) and an external, time-dependent field. The ionization channels may be coupled through various interactions, which may or may not affect the photoelectron. System only describes the channels, the external field, and the interactions possible, the actual process is described by a Diagram.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"reference/#StrongFieldApproximation.System-Tuple{AbstractVector{var\"#s20\"} where var\"#s20\"<:StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationChannel, AbstractVector{T} where T, ElectricFields.AbstractField, Any}","page":"Reference","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.System","text":"System(ionization_channels, couplings, F, ndt)\n\nSet up a System consisting of multiple IonizationChannels with possible couplings between them, driven by an external field F, sampled at ndt times per cycle.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#StrongFieldApproximation.induced_dipole-Tuple{StrongFieldApproximation.System, Diagram}","page":"Reference","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.induced_dipole","text":"induced_dipole(system, diagram[; kwargs...])\n\nCompute the induced dipole moment as a function of time of the System, for a specific Diagram.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"reference/#StrongFieldApproximation.recurse_common-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Amp}, Tuple{Type{Amp}, StrongFieldApproximation.System{T, IonizationChannels, Couplings, Field, Times, Volkov} where {IonizationChannels<:(AbstractVector{var\"#s20\"} where var\"#s20\"<:(StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationChannel{T, SourceTerm} where SourceTerm<:StrongFieldApproximation.AbstractSourceTerm)), Couplings<:(AbstractVector{var\"#s12\"} where var\"#s12\"<:(AbstractMatrix{var\"#s11\"} where var\"#s11\"<:StrongFieldApproximation.AbstractCoupling)), Field<:ElectricFields.AbstractField, Times<:(AbstractVector{T} where T), Volkov<:StrongFieldApproximation.VolkovPhases}, Any, Any, Any, Any, Diagram}} where {Amp, T}","page":"Reference","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.recurse_common","text":"recurse_common(fun, system::System, ùê§, ùê©, iref, irange, Œ±, path; œµ, memory)\n\nAt time t = system.t[iref], we have an interaction, which involves the photoelectrons and the ions:\n\nbeginequation*\nbraalpha\nmatrixelveckV(t)vecp\nketbeta\nendequation*\n\nalpha and veck are given, i.e. this is what we want the interaction to result in. If V(t) does not change the photoelectron momentum, we have vecp=veck, but otherwise, we have to determine the intermediate momentum vecp from the semiclassical action ending at time t and starting at an earlier t_textrmprev, which is the closes preceding event where the photoelectron momentum changed, i.e. a previous scattering or the initial photoionization.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"CurrentModule = StrongFieldApproximation","category":"page"},{"location":"#StrongFieldApproximation.jl","page":"Home","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Documentation for StrongFieldApproximation.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Hartree atomic units are used throughout, unless otherwise specified.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"At the moment, two kind of observables are supported: induced dipole moment and photoelectron spectra. Time integrals are performed numerically, with recursive time integrals limited by a memory, i.e. how many time steps are considered (default is one cycle of the fundamental). Integrals over intermediate photoelectron momenta are performed using the saddle-point method, i.e. given two times, the stationary momentum is given by","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"saddlevecp = -frac1t_2-t_1\nint_t_1^t_2difftau\nvecA(tau)-vecA(T)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"where vecA(t) is the vector potential of the external field, and T is the reference time, at which we usually have vecA(T)=0. The integral is thus approximated as","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"intdiffvecp\nf(vecp)\nce^-im S(vecpab)\napprox\nleft\nfrac2piim(a-b) + epsilon\nright^32\nf(saddlevecp)\nce^-im S(saddlevecpab)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"where","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"S(vecpab)defd\n-frac12\nint_a^bdifftau\nvecp+vecA(tau)-vecA(T)^2","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"and epsilon is an infinitesimal regulator.","category":"page"},{"location":"#High-order-Harmonic-Generation-(HHG)","page":"Home","title":"High-order Harmonic Generation (HHG)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"julia> @field(F) do # Linear polarization\n           Œª = 800.0u\"nm\"\n           I‚ÇÄ = 3e14u\"W/cm^2\"\n           œÑ = 6.2u\"fs\"\n           toff = 10.0u\"fs\"\n           tmax = 13.0u\"fs\"\n           env = :trunc_gauss\n       end;\n\njulia> @field(F2) do # Slightly elliptical polarization\n           Œª = 800.0u\"nm\"\n           I‚ÇÄ = 3e14u\"W/cm^2\"\n           œÑ = 6.2u\"fs\"\n           toff = 10.0u\"fs\"\n           tmax = 13.0u\"fs\"\n           env = :trunc_gauss\n           Œæ = 0.2\n       end;\n\njulia> ndt = 300 # Steps per cycle\n300\n\njulia> I‚Çö = 0.5 # Hydrogen\n0.5\n\njulia> # d will be a vector of scalars\n       system,diagram,d = induced_dipole(I‚Çö, F, ndt, memory=floor(Int, 0.65ndt));\n‚îå Info: Induced dipole calculation\n‚îÇ   system =\n‚îÇ    1-channel System:\n‚îÇ     1. IonizationChannel: I‚Çö = 0.5 Ha = 13.6055 eV\n‚îÇ\n‚îÇ    Linearly polarized field with\n‚îÇ      - I‚ÇÄ = 8.5484e-03 au = 3.0e14 W cm‚Åª¬≤ =>\n‚îÇ        - E‚ÇÄ = 9.2457e-02 au = 47.5435 GV m‚Åª¬π\n‚îÇ        - A‚ÇÄ = 1.6234 au\n‚îÇ      ‚Äì a Fixed carrier @ Œª = 800.0000 nm (T = 2.6685 fs, œâ = 0.0570 Ha = 1.5498 eV)\n‚îÇ      ‚Äì and a Truncated Gaussian envelope of duration 256.3165 jiffies = 6.2000 fs (intensity FWHM; turn-off from 10.0000 fs to 13.0000 fs)\n‚îÇ      ‚Äì U‚Çö = 0.6588 Ha = 17.9276 eV => Œ± = 28.5030 Bohr = 1.5083 nm\n‚îÇ   diagram =\n‚îÇ    Goldstone Diagram:\n‚îÇ       |0‚ü©\n‚îÇ      ‚ï±   ‚ï≤‚áú\n‚îÇ     1‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê§\n‚îî\nProgress: 100%|‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà| Time: 0:00:00\n\njulia> # d2 will be a vector of 3d vectors\n       system2,diagram2,d2 = induced_dipole(I‚Çö, F2, ndt, memory=floor(Int, 0.65ndt));\n‚îå Info: Induced dipole calculation\n‚îÇ   system =\n‚îÇ    1-channel System:\n‚îÇ     1. IonizationChannel: I‚Çö = 0.5 Ha = 13.6055 eV\n‚îÇ\n‚îÇ    Transversely polarized field with\n‚îÇ      - I‚ÇÄ = 8.5484e-03 au = 3.0e14 W cm‚Åª¬≤ =>\n‚îÇ        - E‚ÇÄ = 9.2457e-02 au = 47.5435 GV m‚Åª¬π\n‚îÇ        - A‚ÇÄ = 1.6234 au\n‚îÇ      ‚Äì a Elliptical carrier with Œæ = 0.20 (right) @ Œª = 800.0000 nm (T = 2.6685 fs, œâ = 0.0570 Ha = 1.5498 eV)\n‚îÇ      ‚Äì and a Truncated Gaussian envelope of duration 256.3165 jiffies = 6.2000 fs (intensity FWHM; turn-off from 10.0000 fs to 13.0000 fs)\n‚îÇ      ‚Äì U‚Çö = 0.6588 Ha = 17.9276 eV => Œ± = 28.5030 Bohr = 1.5083 nm\n‚îÇ   diagram =\n‚îÇ    Goldstone Diagram:\n‚îÇ       |0‚ü©\n‚îÇ      ‚ï±   ‚ï≤‚áú\n‚îÇ     1‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê§\n‚îî\nProgress: 100%|‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà| Time: 0:00:00","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"(Image: HHG example)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The dotted vertical line indicates the classical HHG cut-off:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"W_k^textrmmax = 317U_p + I_p","category":"page"},{"location":"#Photoelectron-Spectra","page":"Home","title":"Photoelectron Spectra","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Attosecond-Streaking","page":"Home","title":"Attosecond Streaking","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Attosecond streaking is a method for measuring, among other things, the vector potential of a ultrashort IR pulse. We can simulate this experiment as follows:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"julia> @field(pump) do\n           ƒßœâ = 80u\"eV\"\n           I‚ÇÄ = 1e8u\"W/cm^2\"\n           œÑ = 200u\"as\"\n           toff = 400u\"as\"\n           tmax = 500u\"as\"\n           env = :trunc_gauss\n       end;\n\njulia> @field(probe) do\n           Œª = 800.0u\"nm\"\n           I‚ÇÄ = 1e12u\"W/cm^2\"\n           œÑ = 2.66u\"fs\"\n           toff = 4.0u\"fs\"\n           tmax = 5.0u\"fs\"\n           env = :trunc_gauss\n       end;\n\njulia> F = pump + delay(probe, 1.0u\"fs\");\n\njulia> ndt = 100\n100\n\njulia> nk = 100\n100\n\njulia> nŒ∏ = 2 # Forward and backward spectra only\n2\n\njulia> k,kmag,Œ∏ = momentum_grid(50u\"eV\", 80u\"eV\", nk, nŒ∏,\n                                spacing=:energy);\n\njulia> I‚Çö = 14u\"eV\" # \"Krypton\"\n14 eV\n\njulia> c = photoelectron_spectrum(k, I‚Çö, F, ndt);\n‚îå Info: Photoelectrum spectrum calculation\n‚îÇ   system =\n‚îÇ    1-channel System:\n‚îÇ     1. IonizationChannel: I‚Çö = 0.5144905104572604 Ha = 13.99980128005251 eV\n‚îÇ\n‚îÇ    ‚îå Linearly polarized field with\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ   - I‚ÇÄ = 2.8495e-09 au = 1.0e8 W cm‚Åª¬≤ =>\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ     - E‚ÇÄ = 5.3380e-05 au = 27.4492 MV m‚Åª¬π\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ     - A‚ÇÄ = 0.0000 au\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ   ‚Äì a Fixed carrier @ Œª = 15.4980 nm (T = 51.6958 as, œâ = 2.9399 Ha = 80.0000 eV)\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ   ‚Äì and a Truncated Gaussian envelope of duration 8.2683 jiffies = 200.0000 as (intensity FWHM; turn-off from 400.0000 as to 500.0000 as)\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ   ‚Äì U‚Çö = 0.0000 Ha = 2.2427 neV => Œ± = 0.0000 Bohr = 326.8159 am\n‚îÇ    ‚äï\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ Linearly polarized field with\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ   - I‚ÇÄ = 2.8495e-05 au = 1.0e12 W cm‚Åª¬≤ =>\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ     - E‚ÇÄ = 5.3380e-03 au = 2.7449 GV m‚Åª¬π\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ     - A‚ÇÄ = 0.0937 au\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ   ‚Äì a Fixed carrier @ Œª = 800.0000 nm (T = 2.6685 fs, œâ = 0.0570 Ha = 1.5498 eV)\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ   ‚Äì and a Truncated Gaussian envelope of duration 109.9681 jiffies = 2.6600 fs (intensity FWHM; turn-off from 4.0000 fs to 5.0000 fs)\n‚îÇ    ‚îÇ   ‚Äì U‚Çö = 0.0022 Ha = 59.7587 meV => Œ± = 1.6456 Bohr = 87.0824 pm\n‚îÇ    ‚îî   ‚Äì delayed by 41.3414 jiffies = 1.0000 fs\n‚îÇ\n‚îÇ   diagram =\n‚îÇ    Goldstone Diagram:\n‚îÇ       |0‚ü©\n‚îÇ      ‚ï±   ‚ï≤‚áú\n‚îÇ     1‚îÉ   ‚îÇùê§\n‚îÇ\n‚îî   length(k) = 200","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"(Image: Streaking single delay)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"By sweeping the pump‚Äìprobe delay, we can construct the following streaking spectrogram: (Image: Streaking spectrogram)","category":"page"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"Strong-field ionization","text":"This implements the strong-field ionization formula given by PPT, i.e.","category":"page"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"Strong-field ionization","text":"Perelomov, A., Popov, V., & Terent'ev, M. (1966). Ionization of Atoms in an Alternating Electric Field. Soviet Physics‚ÄîJournal of Experimental and Theoretical Physics, 23(5), 924‚Äì934,","category":"page"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"Strong-field ionization","text":"with some sprinkles of ADK:","category":"page"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"Strong-field ionization","text":"Ammosov, M. V., Delone, N. B., & Krainov, V. P. (1986). Tunnel Ionization of Complex Atoms and of Atomic Ions in Alternating Electromagnetic Field. Soviet Physics‚ÄîJournal of Experimental and Theoretical Physics, 64(6), 1191‚Äì1194.","category":"page"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"Strong-field ionization","text":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.PPT","category":"page"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.PPT","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.PPT","text":"PPT(I‚Çö, I, œâ, ‚Ñì, m[, Z=1])\n\nCompute the strong-field photoionization rate from an initial state with ionization potential I‚Çö, angular quantum numbers ‚Ñì & m, and a binding potential of charge Z, when subjected to monochromatic light of intensity I and angular frequency œâ, using the PPT formalism (slightly generalized to effective principal quantum numbers n^*):\n\nbeginequation\ntagPPT54ADK1\nw_ell m(F omega) =\nI_p\nabsC_n^*ell^*^2\nsqrtfrac32pi\nf(ell m)\ntildeE^-(2n^* - absm - 32)\n(1+gamma^2)^-n^* + absm2 + 34\nA_m(omegagamma)\nexpleft\n-fracg(gamma)3tildeE\nright\nendequation\n\nwhere gamma is the Keldysh parameter, and n^* the effective_n.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"Strong-field ionization","text":"julia> using StrongFieldApproximation, ElectricFields, Unitful, UnitfulAtomic\n\njulia> I = 10 .^ range(10, stop=15, length=100) * u\"W/cm^2\";\n\njulia> Iau = ElectricFields.Iaustrip.(I);\n\njulia> Œª = [400u\"nm\", 800u\"nm\", 2000u\"nm\"]\n3-element Vector{Quantity{Int64, ùêã, Unitful.FreeUnits{(nm,), ùêã, nothing}}}:\n  400 nm\n  800 nm\n 2000 nm\n\njulia> œâ = austrip.(2œÄ*1u\"c\" ./ Œª)\n3-element Vector{Float64}:\n 0.11390838132237764\n 0.05695419066118882\n 0.022781676264475526\n\njulia> I‚Çö = 0.5 # Hydrogen\n0.5\n\njulia> rates = StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.PPT.(I‚Çö, Iau, œâ', 0, 0);","category":"page"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"Strong-field ionization","text":"(Image: PPT example)","category":"page"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#Internals-reference","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"Internals reference","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"Strong-field ionization","text":"Modules = [StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates]\nFilter = !isequal(StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.PPT)","category":"page"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.A-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.A","text":"A(m, I‚Çö, I, œâ[; tol = ‚àö(eps()), maxterms=typemax(Int)])\n\nbeginequation\ntagPPT55\nA_m(omegagamma) =\nfrac4sqrt3pi\nfrac1absm\nfracgamma^21+gamma^2\nsum_ngeqnu^infty\nexp-alpha(n-nu)\nw_msqrtbeta(n-nu)\nendequation\n\nwhere nu is computed using ŒΩ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.C2-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.C2","text":"beginequation\ntagADK19\nabsC_n^*ell^*^2 =\nfrac2^2n^*n^*Gamma(n^*+ell^*+1)Gamma(n^*-ell^*)\nendequation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.Etilde-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.Etilde","text":"Etilde(E0, I‚Çö)\n\ntildeE = fracE_02(2I_p)^32 equiv\nfracsqrtI2(2I_p)^32\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.effective_n-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.effective_n","text":"effective_n(I‚Çö, Z)\n\nEffective principal quantum number for ionization potential I‚Çö and residual nuclear charge Z.\n\nbeginequation\ntagADK2\nn^* = fracZsqrt2I_p\nendequation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.f-Tuple{Integer, Integer}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.f","text":"f(‚Ñì, m)\n\nCommon prefactor appearing in e.g Eqs. (PPT54,59), (ADK12)\n\nf(ell m) =\nfrac(2ell+1)(ell+absm)\n2^absm(absm)(ell-absm)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.g-Tuple{Any}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.g","text":"g(Œ≥)\n\nbeginequation\ntagPPT33\ng(gamma) =\nfrac32gamma\nleft\nleft(\n1+frac12gamma^2\nright)\narcsinhgamma-\nfracsqrt1+gamma^22gamma\nright equiv\nfrac32gamma\nleft\nleft(\n1+frac12gamma^2\nright)\narcsinhgamma-\nfrac1beta(gamma)\nright\nendequation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.w-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.w","text":"w(m,x)\n\nbeginequation\ntagPPT56\nw_m(x) =\nfracx^2absm+12\nint_0^1difft\nfracexp(-x^2t)t^absmsqrt1-t\nendequation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.Œ±-Tuple{Any}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.Œ±","text":"Œ±(Œ≥)\n\nbeginequation\ntagPPT34\nalpha(gamma) =\n2left(\narcsinhgamma -\nfracgammasqrt1+gamma^2\nright) equiv\n2arcsinhgamma -\nbeta(gamma)\nendequation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.Œ≤-Tuple{Any}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.Œ≤","text":"Œ≤(Œ≥)\n\nbeginequation\ntagPPT56ff\nbeta(gamma) =\nfrac2gammasqrt1+gamma^2\nendequation\n\nDefined just below Eq. (PPT56).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"strong_field_ionization/#StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.ŒΩ-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"Strong-field ionization","title":"StrongFieldApproximation.IonizationRates.ŒΩ","text":"ŒΩ(I‚Çö, I, œâ)\n\nNumber of photons of energy omega needed to reach above the ionization potential I_p in the presence of a strong dressing field of intensity I.\n\nbeginequation\ntagPPT26\nnu = fracI_pomega\nleft(1+frac12gamma^2right)\nendequation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"}]
